===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|かみ|yomi=k|alt=帋}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|紙}}, cited to manuscript kana glosses in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720 {{CE}},<ref name="KDJC">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten Concise}}</ref> from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|sort=かみ|*kanpi}} (the modern standard Japanese form results from a sporadic change of {{IPAchar|[ᵐb]}} to {{IPAchar|[m]}}). Cognate with {{cog|ryu|紙|tr=kabi}}. Compare also {{cog|ain|カㇺピ|t=paper|tr=kampi}}, from Proto-Ainu *kanpi (which is assumed to have been borrowed from Japonic<ref>{{cite-book|page=19|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Len4EAAAQBAJ&pg=PA19|chapter=Reconstruction of Japonic and para-Japonic based on external sources|title=Handbook of Historical Japanese Linguistics|year=2024|author=Alexander Vovin}}</ref>).

An alternative hypothesis explains the Old Japanese word as a borrowing from {{bor|ja|ltc|簡|t=bamboo slip used for writing}}, with a shift in pronunciation from ''kan''<ref name="DDJS">{{R:Digital-Daijisen}}</ref> → *{{IPAchar|/kamu/}} → {{IPAchar|/kami/}}, with [[excrescent]] final ''-i'' as in {{m|ja|文|tr=fumi}} from borrowed ''bun'' or ''pun''.  That would require the forms based on {{IPAchar|[ᵐb]}} to result from the sporadic change of {{IPAchar|[m]}} to {{IPAchar|[ᵐb]}}, as in {{m|ja|黍|ts=kibi|t=millet}} from Old Japanese {{m|ojp|黍|寸三|ts=ki₁mi₁}}.  However, Ryukyuan reflexes appear to maintain a {{IPAchar|/b/}} phone, which is more difficult to explain for a borrowing from Chinese.

